          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which of the following correctly identifies the transpyloric plane?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which of the following correctly identifies the transpyloric plane?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It lies at vertebral level L4, connecting the highest points of the iliac crests</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This describes the supracristal plane at L4, not the transpyloric plane.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It lies at vertebral level L1, midway between the jugular notch and the pubic symphysis</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The transpyloric plane at L1 crosses the pylorus, pancreatic neck, superior mesenteric artery origin, and both renal hila — making it the most landmark-rich abdominal plane.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It passes through the umbilicus and divides the abdomen into upper and lower halves</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This describes the transumbilical plane, which is used to create the four-quadrant system — not the transpyloric plane.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It lies at vertebral level L3 and marks the origin of the inferior mesenteric artery</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The inferior mesenteric artery arises at L3, well below the transpyloric plane which is at L1.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the transpyloric plane: L1 level, midway jugular notch to pubic symphysis, crossing the pylorus, pancreatic neck, SMA origin, and both renal hila."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "The transpyloric plane at L1 is the single most landmark-rich horizontal plane — remember it as the 'anatomist's favourite' reference line."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
