          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Extravasated urine from a ruptured membranous urethra spreads to the scrotum and</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Extravasated urine from a ruptured membranous urethra spreads to the scrotum and perineum but cannot reach the thigh. Which structure prevents this spread?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Camper's fascia</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Camper's fascia is the superficial fatty layer. It does not form a restrictive fascial barrier at the inguinal ligament.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Scarpa's fascia</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Scarpa's fascia (the deeper membranous layer) fuses with the fascia lata of the thigh just below the inguinal ligament, creating a sealed compartment that confines extravasated fluid to the abdomen, scrotum, and perineum.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Transversalis fascia</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Transversalis fascia lines the deep surface of the abdominal wall muscles. It is unrelated to the superficial spread of extravasated urine.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>External oblique aponeurosis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The external oblique aponeurosis is a muscular layer deep to both fascial layers of the superficial fascia. It does not restrict superficial fluid spread.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember the two layers: Camper's (fatty, superficial) and Scarpa's (membranous, deeper). Scarpa's fuses with the deep fascia of the thigh below the inguinal ligament, preventing urine from reaching the thigh."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Scarpa's fascia fusing with the fascia lata is a classic exam point — it explains the clinical pattern of perineal and scrotal swelling without thigh involvement."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
