          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>An indirect inguinal hernia enters the inguinal canal through the deep ring. Wha</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>An indirect inguinal hernia enters the inguinal canal through the deep ring. What is its relationship to the inferior epigastric vessels?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Medial to the inferior epigastric vessels</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A hernia medial to the inferior epigastric vessels is a direct hernia — it pushes through Hesselbach's triangle, not the deep ring.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lateral to the inferior epigastric vessels</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The MALL mnemonic helps: Medial = direct (through Hesselbach's triangle), Lateral = indirect (through the deep ring). Indirect hernias have higher strangulation risk because the tight deep ring can constrict the herniated contents.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Posterior to the inferior epigastric vessels</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hernia classification depends on the medial–lateral relationship to the inferior epigastric vessels, not an anterior–posterior one.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Within Hesselbach's triangle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hesselbach's triangle (bounded by rectus medially, inferior epigastric vessels laterally, inguinal ligament inferiorly) is the site of direct hernias, not indirect hernias.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Use MALL: Medial → direct (Hesselbach's triangle), Lateral → indirect (deep ring). The inferior epigastric vessels are the single most important landmark for classifying inguinal hernias at surgery."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Lateral to the vessels = indirect = through the deep ring. This is the commonest type in young males because the deep ring marks where the testis descended during fetal life."
                }
              ],
